suffrage?  No one under 18 can vote - does that mean every decision made by our government wasn't democratic?<br>
<br>
The same arguement can be applied to the Revolutionary War, by the way.  Women didn't get to vote . . . they had no say in the matter, so that wasn't democracy either.<br>
<br>
So if you argue that the Southern States seceding wasn't a democratic decision, because black people weren't allowed to vote on it, then I respond that the Declaration of Independence wasn't either, because women couldn't vote on that.<br>
<br>
All democracies have restrictions, for whatever reasons (some good, some not) on who can vote.  Historically, these have usually been age, race, sex, wealth, and in some nations religion.  This doesn't eliminate the fact that decisions voted on WERE voted on democratically.  <br>
<br>
I'm not defending slavery, because I don't think slavery is right, never have.  BUT, and here's the catch - the Federal Government wasn't taking any action to eliminate slavery - that came about as a tactic to disrupt the Southern economy (if you can call it that) and lifestyle, and frankly worked pretty well to do so.  Smart strategic and PR move.<br>
<br>
The Federal Govenment did not go to war to tell the southern states they had to free their slaves - it went to war to force the Southern States to stay in the Union.  It wasn't about slavery, it was about whether or not individual states had the right to dissolve their membership in the United States of America. <p></br>

<img src=http://home.attbi.com/~shay01/morksiggy.gif
>


</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/udandaeluswyldheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dandaelus Wyldheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/23/02 3:26:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The War of Northern Agression (aka Civil War)</span><hr size=1> Before reading this, understand that I am an American and love my country. With all of its faults it is still the best country to live in in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Democracy has been a farce since the constitution was written.<br>
The writers of the constitution felt that the average person was neither educated nor informed ehough to be able to make a descision on what should be made into a law or who should be in charge, thus they instituted the current voting laws to include the electoral vote.<br>
<br>
The electoral vote is so unfair that the country is no longer what we originally fought for, FREEDOM. The lack of a direct vote has made the ideals of a government by the people a farce.<br>
4 times in our past electoral voters voted against the majority of thier state, and 2 times a president with the majority of votes lost the election.<br>
<br>
In a goverenment led by old rich people how can we be an accurate representation of the people. You cant get elected to office unless you have money to run a campaign. Once a person is voted into office they run the government by cronyism. <br>
<br>
Every president we have had has been separated from the people they govern by a generation, and sometimes by 2 genrations. When we have people in charge of us who are making descision based on ideas and beliefs that dont coincide with the current change of the nation, we are doomed to forever be behind the power curve.<br>
<br>
So yes, the civil war was a farce upon the government, but nothing as bad as it has become lately. <p><a href=mailto:Dandaelus@allakhazam.com>Dandaelus Wyldheart</a>
